2024-6%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EDell's%20workforce%3C%2Fa%3E%20was%20a%20collective%20shrug.%20Months%20after%20the%20directive%2C%20nearly%20half%20of%20employees%20were%20still%20remote%2C%20apparently%20happy%20to%20remain%20in%20their%20current%20roles%20as%20long%20as%20they%20could%20keep%20working%20from%20home.%20It%20was%20a%20clear%20sign%20that%20in%202024%2C%20promotions%20just%20aren't%20the%20incentive%20they%20used%20to%20be.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAt%20stake%2C%20though%2C%20is%20something%20much%20larger%20than%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Famazon-workers-blast-strict-rto-mandate-five-days-week-2024-9%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3ERTO%20wars%3C%2Fa%3E.%20After%20all%2C%20careerism%20has%20long%20played%20an%20essential%20role%20in%20building%20dynamic%20and%20successful%20companies.%20The%20prospect%20of%20becoming%20senior%20vice%20president%20is%20what%20drove%20so%20many%20white-collar%20professionals%20to%20give%20it%20their%20all%2C%20even%20in%20the%20face%20of%20long%20hours%2C%20soul-crushing%20meetings%2C%20and%20petty%20office%20politics.%20If%20the%20allure%20of%20promotions%20can%20no%20longer%20get%20everyone%20to%20work%20hard%2C%20what%20will%3F%3C%2Fp%3E%3Chr%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20dream%20of%20climbing%20the%20corporate%20ladder%20feels%20as%20old%20as%20America%20itself.%20But%20200%20years%20ago%2C%20there%20was%20no%20corporate%20ladder%20to%20climb.%20The%20original%20work%20ethic%20in%20America%20%E2%80%94%20the%20Protestant%20one%2C%20espoused%20by%20the%20likes%20of%20Benjamin%20Franklin%20%E2%80%94%20dates%20from%20a%20time%20when%20most%20Americans%20were%20self-employed%20as%20farmers%20and%20artisans.%20It%20was%20rooted%20in%20a%20rugged%20individualism%20that%20was%20skeptical%20of%20authority%20and%20hierarchies%2C%20fitting%20for%20a%20country%20founded%20on%20the%20idea%20of%20freedom%20from%20tyranny.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThat%20became%20a%20problem%20when%20the%20Industrial%20Revolution%20arrived.%20Companies%20exploded%20in%20size%2C%20and%20more%20and%20more%20Americans%20found%20themselves%20working%20for%20someone%20else.%20In%201820%2C%2080%25%20of%20the%20workforce%20was%20self-employed.%20By%201870%2C%20that%20share%20had%20shrunk%20to%2033%25.%20By%201940%2C%20it%20was%2020%25.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BThe%20moral%20vision%20of%20American%20society%20had%20been%20based%20upon%20the%20image%20of%20the%20independent%2C%20self-employed%20person%2C%26quot%3B%20writes%20Shoshana%20Zuboff%2C%20a%20professor%20emeritus%20at%20the%20Harvard%20Business%20School%20who%20has%20studied%20the%20history%20of%20work.%20%26quot%3BMany%20social%20critics%20feared%20that%20people%20would%20be%20less%20likely%20to%20work%20hard%20under%20the%20wage%20system%20and%2C%20even%20worse%2C%20that%20something%20in%20their%20very%20natures%20might%20change.%26quot%3B%20America%20was%20facing%20an%20identity%20crisis.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20solution%20was%20to%20forge%20a%20whole%20new%20work%20ethic%20%E2%80%94%20one%20that%20celebrated%20the%20sprawling%20corporate%20hierarchies%20that%20were%20swallowing%20up%20most%20Americans.%20The%20ideal%20was%20no%20longer%20independence%20but%20%3Cem%3Einter%3C%2Fem%3Edependence%2C%20a%20willingness%20to%20be%20subsumed%20by%20the%20needs%20of%20the%20larger%20whole.%20%26quot%3BWhat%20the%20managers%20of%20these%20new%20enterprises%20now%20needed%20to%20induce%20was%20obedience%20and%20efficiency%2C%26quot%3B%20writes%20Zuboff%2C%20%26quot%3Bnot%20the%20questioning%20stubborn%20ways%20of%20the%20autonomous%20crafts%20person%20idealized%20by%20the%20old%20work%20ethic.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThis%20new%20%26quot%3Bcareer%20ethic%26quot%3B%20came%20with%20a%20carrot.%20By%20serving%20as%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Floyalty-employee-employer-job-security-broken-work-companies-bosses-2024-1%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eloyal%20soldiers%20for%20their%20companies%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20employees%20could%20expect%20to%20gain%20more%20prestige%2C%20better%20job%20security%2C%20and%20bigger%20salaries.%20Help%20the%20boss%2C%20professionals%20were%20told%2C%20and%20maybe%20you%20can%20%3Cem%3Ebecome%20%3C%2Fem%3Ethe%20boss.%20The%20new%20ethic%20took%20hold%20among%20the%20managerial%20class%20in%20the%201950s.%20By%20the%201970s%2C%20it%20had%20spread%20to%20the%20entire%20workforce.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EHalf%20a%20century%20later%2C%20the%20careerist%20ethos%20is%20still%20the%20bible%20of%20the%20corporate%20workplace.%20Those%20who%20try%20to%20opt%20out%20risk%20getting%20blacklisted%20as%20weirdos%20or%20losers%20or%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Foverachievers-leaning-back-hustle-culture-coasting-employees-work%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Equiet%20quitters%3C%2Fa%3E.%20But%20cracks%20are%20starting%20to%20appear%20in%20the%20system%3A%20Many%20people%2C%20it%20has%20become%20clear%2C%20are%20no%20longer%20willing%20to%20make%20the%20trade-offs%20required%20by%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fhustle-culture-got-america-addicted-to-work%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EAmerica's%20hustle%20culture%3C%2Fa%3E.%20And%20the%20number%20of%20promotion%20deniers%20would%20likely%20be%20even%20higher%20if%20employees%20weren't%20worried%20about%20outing%20themselves%20as%20non-careerists.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EOne%20guy%20I%20spoke%20with%2C%20a%20systems%20analyst%20I'll%20call%20James%2C%20is%20desperate%20to%20avoid%20the%20promotion%20his%20boss%20keeps%20hinting%20at.%20But%20he's%20worried%20about%20the%20consequences%20of%20turning%20it%20down.%20%26quot%3BIf%20I%20told%20him%20I%20don't%20want%20to%20go%20any%20further%2C%20I%20feel%20like%20he'll%20start%20passing%20me%20over%20for%20new%20ideas%20he%20has%2C%26quot%3B%20James%20told%20me.%20%26quot%3BFor%20some%20reason%2C%20in%20our%20society%20in%20America%2C%20that's%20kind%20of%20shunned.%20People%20are%20expected%20to%20want%20to%20keep%20climbing%20and%20climbing.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Chr%3E%3Cp%3EZack%2C%20who's%20in%20his%20early%2040s%2C%20was%20one%20of%20those%20people%20eager%20to%20keep%20climbing.%20As%20an%20apprentice%2C%20he%20dreamed%20of%20becoming%20a%20foreman.%20And%20once%20he%20became%20a%20foreman%2C%20he%20aspired%20for%20even%20higher%20positions.%20%26quot%3BI%20wanted%20to%20run%20the%20largest%20jobs%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20says.%20%26quot%3BI%20wanted%20to%20gain%20the%20most%20experience.%20I%20wanted%20to%20run%20the%20biggest%20crews.%26quot%3B%20Eventually%2C%20he%20got%20promoted%20into%20a%20corporate%20office%20role%2C%20and%20that%20opened%20up%20even%20more%20opportunities%20for%20advancement.%20%26quot%3BI%20was%20fairly%20ambitious%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20says.%20%26quot%3BAnd%20it%20worked%20out%20really%20well.%26quot%3B%20He%20rose%20all%20the%20way%20to%20head%20up%20an%20entire%20department.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBut%20when%20the%20pandemic%20hit%2C%20he%20started%20questioning%20that%20upward%20trajectory.%20The%20first%20jolt%20was%20when%20his%20job%20went%20remote%20during%20the%20shutdown.%20%3Cspan%3EWorking%20from%20home%2C%20he%20realized%20just%20how%20much%20he'd%20been%20missing%20out%20on.%20%26quot%3BAt%20lunchtime%2C%20I%20could%20go%20running%20for%2045%20minutes%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20recalls.%20%26quot%3BAll%20these%20things%20I%20used%20to%20love%20to%20do%2C%20I%20started%20doing%20again.%20I%20was%20like%2C%20oh%20my%20God%2C%20I%20never%20want%20to%20give%20up%20this%20life.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%223080%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22A%20man%20refusing%20to%20follow%20another%20man%20holding%20a%20sword%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F670d7b483f2165d716e0b3cc%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%222363%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3E%3Cp%3EJames%20Yates%20for%20BI%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EThen%2C%20even%20before%20the%20rest%20of%20the%20economy%20began%20to%20open%20up%2C%20his%20bosses%20pressured%20Zack%20to%20force%20his%20team%20to%20come%20back%20to%20the%20office.%20He%20was%20stunned.%20Some%20of%20his%20employees%20had%20family%20members%20who%20were%20immunocompromised%3B%20an%20RTO%20order%20could%20endanger%20their%20lives.%20%26quot%3BThat%20was%20a%20betrayal%20from%20a%20company%20I%20had%20been%20incredibly%20dedicated%20to%2C%26quot%3B%20Zack%20told%20me.%20%26quot%3BAfter%20that%2C%20I%20was%20like%2C%20well%2C%20fuck.%20I%20was%20dedicated%20to%20this%20thing%2C%20and%20it%20was%20all%20a%20big%20fucking%20lie.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ERather%20than%20toe%20the%20company%20line%2C%20Zack%20quit.%20He%20found%20a%20job%20that%20didn't%20require%20him%20to%20be%20a%20manager%2C%20and%20took%20a%20%2420%2C000%20pay%20cut.%20Today%20he%20far%20prefers%20being%20an%20individual%20contributor%20who's%20free%20to%20focus%20on%20his%20own%20work%20%E2%80%94%20another%20reason%20he%20declined%20the%20promotion%20he%20was%20offered%20last%20year.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EProfessionals%20younger%20than%20Zack%2C%20who's%20an%20elder%20millennial%2C%20appear%20to%20harbor%20an%20even%20stronger%20anti-advancement%20streak.%20In%20Randstad's%20survey%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fgen-z-hot-jobs-tech-layoffs-healthcare-government-careers-2024-7%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EGen%20Z%3C%2Fa%3E%20respondents%20%E2%80%94%20those%20on%20the%20lowest%20rungs%20of%20the%20corporate%20ladder%2C%20earning%20the%20lowest%20salaries%20%E2%80%94%20were%20more%20likely%20than%20millennials%20or%20Gen%20Xers%20to%20agree%20with%20the%20statement%20%26quot%3BI%20don't%20want%20career%20progression.%26quot%3B%20In%20another%20survey%2C%20when%20Gallup%20asked%20people%20what's%20deterring%20them%20from%20seeking%20a%20position%20in%20senior%20leadership%2C%20Gen%20Zers%20were%20especially%20concerned%20with%20the%20long%20hours%20and%20round-the-clock%20demands%20that%20come%20with%20a%20job%20at%20the%20top.%20For%20a%20new%20generation%2C%20the%20age%20of%20American%20careerism%20is%20losing%20its%20appeal.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Chr%3E%3Cp%3EOlder%20bosses%20might%20be%20inclined%20to%20chalk%20all%20this%20up%20to%20a%20lack%20of%20ambition%20%E2%80%94%20a%20sign%20that%20young%20people%20aren't%20willing%20to%20put%20in%20the%20effort.%20But%20I%20think%20it%20makes%20sense%20that%20the%20allure%20of%20career%20progression%20is%20fading%2C%20given%20how%20much%20the%20workplace%20has%20changed%20in%20recent%20decades.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ETake%20job%20security.%20Back%20in%20the%201960s%2C%20managers%20had%20nothing%20to%20fear%20from%20layoffs%2C%20because%20layoffs%20were%20basically%20unheard%20of.%20But%20today%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fmiddle-managers-great-flattening-organization-meta-tech-layoffs-firing-2023-3%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ebeing%20a%20manager%3C%2Fa%3E%20puts%20a%20huge%20target%20on%20your%20back%2C%20because%20you%20earn%20a%20bigger%20salary.%20If%20you%20accept%20a%20promotion%20you%20might%20wind%20up%20being%20%3Cem%3Emore%20%3C%2Fem%3Eexpendable%2C%20rather%20than%20less.%20That%20elevated%20risk%20is%20the%20main%20reason%20that%20James%2C%20the%20systems%20analyst%2C%20plans%20to%20decline%20his%20impending%20promotion.%20%26quot%3BThey%20always%20do%20layoffs%20every%20two%20or%20three%20years%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20says%20of%20his%20employer.%20%26quot%3BI%20don't%20want%20to%20come%20up%20higher%20on%20the%20list%20as%20someone%20who's%20getting%20paid%20more.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBesides%2C%20the%20dream%20of%20climbing%20the%20corporate%20ladder%20was%20probably%20never%20as%20great%20as%20it%20seemed%20to%20be.%20Often%2C%20people%20get%20promoted%20only%20to%20find%20themselves%20doing%20less%20of%20the%20meaningful%20work%20that%20attracted%20them%20to%20their%20profession%20in%20the%20first%20place.%20This%20is%20such%20a%20common%20problem%2C%20in%20fact%2C%20that%20management%20scholars%20have%20a%20special%20term%20for%20it%3A%20%3Cem%3Emanagerial%20blues%3C%2Fem%3E.%20It's%20the%20sad%20irony%20of%20corporate%20America%3A%20The%20higher%20up%20you%20go%2C%20the%20less%20fulfilling%20your%20job%20becomes.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BEverybody%20wants%20to%20be%20the%20VP%20or%20the%20partner%20with%20the%20corner%20office%2C%26quot%3B%20says%20Michel%20Anteby%2C%20a%20professor%20of%20management%20and%20organizations%20at%20Boston%20University.%20%26quot%3BThe%20imaginary%20is%20that%20life%20will%20be%20much%20better%20then.%20But%20in%20fact%20you%20might%20be%20losing%20out%20on%20something%20that's%20very%20meaningful%20to%20you.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ESo%20how%20can%20companies%20motivate%20employees%20to%20work%20hard%2C%20if%20promotions%20have%20lost%20their%20appeal%3F%20I%20posed%20that%20question%20to%20Zack.%20Given%20how%20betrayed%20he%20felt%20by%20his%20previous%20employer%2C%20I%20wondered%20if%20he%20no%20longer%20believes%20in%20dedicating%20himself%20to%20his%20job%2C%20no%20matter%20the%20potential%20rewards.%20But%20it%20turns%20out%20there%20are%20still%20plenty%20of%20things%20that%20motivate%20him.%20Getting%20to%20do%20interesting%20work.%20Having%20the%20autonomy%20to%20create%20his%20own%20schedule.%20Feeling%20like%20a%20trusted%20and%20valued%20member%20of%20the%20team.%20Being%20surrounded%20by%20peers%20who%20are%20great%20at%20what%20they%20do.%20Reporting%20to%20a%20manager%20who%20actually%2C%20in%20his%20words%2C%20%26quot%3Bgives%20a%20shit.%26quot%3B%20Those%20are%20the%20things%20that%20light%20a%20fire%20under%20him.%20%26quot%3BI%20do%20work%20extra%2C%26quot%3B%20Zack%20says.%20%26quot%3BI%20really%20do%20try%20hard.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhen%20I%20asked%20James%20what%20drives%20him%2C%20he%20said%20something%20similar.%20%26quot%3BI%20like%20my%20job%20and%20I%20want%20to%20keep%20getting%20better%20at%20it%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20told%20me.%20%26quot%3BAnd%20since%20I%20work%20at%